05683nam a22008895i 9780674063204DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2011    mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740632047 a10.4159/harvard.97806740632042doi  a(DE-B1597)178126  a(OCoLC)768411322  a(OCoLC)979683594  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aD514 -- M35 2011eb 7aHIS0270902bisacsh04a940.3/111 aMcMeekin, Sean, eauthor.14aThe Russian Origins of the First World War /cSean McMeekin. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource :b16 halftones, 10 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00t Frontmatter -- tContents -- tMaps -- tAbbreviations -- tAuthor's Note -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. The Strategic Imperative in 1914 -- tChapter Two. It Takes Two to Tango -- tChapter Three. Russia's War -- tChapter Four. Turkey's Turn -- tChapter Five. The Russians and Gallipoli -- tChapter Six. Russia and the Armenians -- tChapter Seven. The Russians in Persia -- tChapter Eight. Partitioning the Ottoman Empire -- tChapter Nine. 1917 -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe catastrophe of the First World War, and the destruction, revolution, and enduring hostilities it wrought, make the issue of its origins a perennial puzzle. Since World War II, Germany has been viewed as the primary culprit. Now, in a major reinterpretation of the conflict, Sean McMeekin rejects the standard notions of the war's beginning as either a Germano-Austrian preemptive strike or a "tragedy of miscalculation." Instead, he proposes that the key to the outbreak of violence lies in St. Petersburg.It was Russian statesmen who unleashed the war through conscious policy decisions based on imperial ambitions in the Near East. Unlike their civilian counterparts in Berlin, who would have preferred to localize the Austro-Serbian conflict, Russian leaders desired a more general war so long as British participation was assured. The war of 1914 was launched at a propitious moment for harnessing the might of Britain and France to neutralize the German threat to Russia's goal: partitioning the Ottoman Empire to ensure control of the Straits between the Black Sea and the Mediterranean.Nearly a century has passed since the guns fell silent on the western front. But in the lands of the former Ottoman Empire, World War I smolders still. Sunnis and Shiites, Arabs and Jews, and other regional antagonists continue fighting over the last scraps of the Ottoman inheritance. As we seek to make sense of these conflicts, McMeekin's powerful exposé of Russia's aims in the First World War will illuminate our understanding of the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 7aHISTORY / Military / World War I.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2011z9783110261189oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PACKAGE ENGLISH LANGUAGES TITLES 2011z978311026123308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET PHILOSOPHIE UND GESCHICHTE 2011z9783110261257oZDB-23-DGE08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP Complete eBook Package 2011-2014z978311037488908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package 2011z978311037492608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045951708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066256640uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067